6","1501":"1501","1400":"1400","1477":"1477","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","8 March 1420":"8 March 1420","Torthorwald, Dumfries-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Torthorwald, Dumfries-Shire, Scotland":"Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kirkpatrick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from either of two places in Dumfriess called Kirkpatrick or any of various other places in Scotland, all so named from the dedication of their church to Saint Patrick. The Scottish word <i>kirk</i> sometimes replaced Gaelic <i>cill</i> ‘church’ in placenames; compare   Kilpatrick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilpatrick","meanings":["Irish (Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phádraig</b> ‘son of the servant of (Saint) Patrick’ (Irish <i>Pádraig</i>). See also   Fitzpatrick  .","Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called in Gaelic as <i>cill Padraig</i> ‘church of (Saint) Patrick’. See also   Kirkpatrick  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Kirkpatrick was born on 8 March 1420, in Scotland, her father, Sir Thomas Kirkpatrick, was 20 and her mother, Maria Maxwell, was 11417. She had at least 2 sons with John Carlyle. She died in 1476, at the age of 56."},"et":{"8 March 1420–1476":"8. märts 1420–1476","1420–1476":"1420–1476","1419–1501":"1419–1501","1446–1477":"1446–1477","1447–1477":"1447–1477","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1408–Female":"1408–Surnud","1447":"1447","1446":"1446","1501":"1501","1400":"1400","1477":"1477","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","8 March 1420":"8. märts 1420","Torthorwald, Dumfries-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Torthorwald, Dumfries-Shire, Scotland":"Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"8 March 1420–1476":"8. maaliskuuta 1420–1476","1420–1476":"1420–1476","1419–1501":"1419–1501","1446–1477":"1446–1477","1447–1477":"1447–1477","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1408–Female":"1408–Kuollut","1447":"1447","1446":"1446","1501":"1501","1400":"1400","1477":"1477","1476":"1476","1420":"1420","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","8 March 1420":"8. maaliskuuta 1420","Torthorwald, Dumfries-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Torthorwald, Dumfries-Shire, Scotland":"Torthorwald, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"8 March 1420–1476":"8 mars 1420–1476","1420–1476":"1420–1476","1419–1501":"1419–1501","1446–1477":"1446–1477","1447–1477":"1447–1477","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","1408–Female":"1408–Décédée","14